-## Matching AI Roles to the Architecture Bottleneck
+## The MAS Approach: Rejecting the Monolithic Oracle
+
+The architectural design loop cannot be solved by a single, monolithic AI oracle. While large language models (LLMs) exhibit remarkable generalized reasoning, the sheer complexity of modern CPU and SoC design radically exceeds the capacity of any single context window. Attempting to force an entire hardware design problem—spanning RTL logic, memory coherence protocols, thermal constraints, and physical routing—into one prompt inevitably leads to "token bloat." As the context grows, the model loses track of critical invariants, hallucinating changes that break physical constraints or violate the system's baseline requirements.
+
+Instead of a monolithic oracle, we must structure AI as a **Multi-Agent System (MAS)**, mirroring the strict separation of concerns found in a human engineering team. A human hardware team does not rely on one engineer to simultaneously draft the RTL, write the compiler backend, and perform the physical layout. They employ specialists. Similarly, the AI architecture must be decoupled into specialized agents—generators, predictors, optimizers, and critics—each bounded by a specific role, distinct state, and a narrow set of legal actions.

-The design loop has distinct bottlenecks. Design-space exploration,
-workload characterization, benchmark construction, code generation, RTL
-repair, compiler/runtime tuning, accelerator search, chiplet partitioning,
-physical-design assistance, and evidence critique are not the same problem.
-They require different state, allow different actions, tolerate different
-errors, and require different feedback.
+This separation of concerns directly addresses the bottlenecks of the design loop. Design-space exploration, workload characterization, RTL repair, and physical-design assistance are fundamentally different problems. They require different state representations, tolerate different error margins, and demand different feedback mechanisms. By assigning a specialized AI role to a specific bottleneck, we constrain the model's authority to a verifiable scope. A generator agent can propose spatial dataflows; a predictor agent can estimate their throughput; an optimizer agent can select the most promising subset. Crucially, none of these agents has the unilateral authority to finalize a design. They operate as a coordinated, multi-agent system where outputs are passed across interfaces and validated by independent tools at every boundary.

