-## Prediction Estimates Consequences Within a Valid Region {#sec-prediction-estimating-behavior-before-full-evaluation}
+## Hospital Admin Tiered Oversight: Prediction and Verification
+
+When composing prediction and verification roles, we must apply a framework of **tiered oversight**, analogous to hospital administration and clinical triage. In a medical setting, a triage nurse (or a diagnostic algorithm) performs the initial assessment, flagging critical issues and prioritizing patients based on fast, approximate vital signs. However, the triage nurse does not prescribe surgery; that authority rests exclusively with the attending physician, who bases decisions on rigorous, high-fidelity clinical tests.
+
+In Architecture 2.0, an AI predictor acts as the triage nurse. It can rapidly estimate consequences, flag impossible thermal profiles, and prioritize promising design candidates based on learned heuristics and analytical proxies. It provides a vital acceleration of the exploration phase. However, the predictor has zero authority to finalize an architectural decision. Only the "attending physician"—the ground-truth simulator, the formal verification solver, or the physical synthesis tool—can authorize the design to move forward.
+
+This strict hierarchy of authority is essential for preventing catastrophic errors. Conformal prediction bounds and surrogate confidence scores are merely diagnostic flags; they are not architectural evidence. Treating a fast, approximate proxy predictor as a ground-truth oracle inevitably invites severe **Out-of-Distribution failures**. When the design search drifts into novel, untested physical regimes, the proxy will confidently hallucinate performance gains that violate fundamental physical laws. By enforcing tiered oversight, the system ensures that AI predictors accelerate the search without ever bypassing the rigorous, independent verification required to trust the outcome.
+
