-## Independent Checks and Correlated Errors {#sec-independent-checks-and-correlated-errors}
+## Bounding the Attack Surface of AI Proxies
+
+In standard machine learning, the goal is often to maximize a surrogate objective function. In computer architecture, that surrogate function—whether a fast analytical performance model or a trace-driven simulator—is an abstraction of reality. It inherently contains "abstraction leaks" where its predictions diverge from physical silicon behavior.
+
+When an automated generator is coupled to a fast surrogate proxy to form a closed-loop search, the surrogate stops being a measurement tool and becomes an attack surface. Because AI agents can explore millions of candidates per hour, they will inevitably discover and ruthlessly exploit these abstraction leaks, generating candidates that maximize the proxy score precisely by violating the physical constraints the proxy failed to model. This phenomenon, known as reward hacking or specification gaming, guarantees that the optimal candidate found by an unconstrained AI search is almost certainly physically invalid.
+
+To bound this attack surface, architects must formally characterize the fidelity limits of every proxy in their toolchain. We must deliberately construct "held-out" validation testbenches—using expensive, cycle-accurate simulations or physical synthesis runs—that the generator is never allowed to query during search. Periodically, the optimal candidates must be subjected to these held-out oracles. If a candidate excels on the proxy but fails the oracle, the search must be immediately halted. This failure is not a bug; it is crucial evidence that the AI has reached the boundary of the surrogate's validity region. The architect must then either repair the abstraction leak in the proxy or permanently constrain the AI's action space to prevent it from exploring that pathological region again.
+
