+Why does the introduction of AI into a hardware study so often degrade the scientific integrity of the result?
+
+::: {.callout-lighthouse}
+**Lighthouse prompt:** Design a low-power, 64-bit RISC-V-based compute subsystem for an autonomous aerial drone capable of running real-time SLAM...
+:::
+
+Consider a research team evaluating an AI-generated SLAM accelerator for our Lighthouse drone. They initialize the model, which outputs a highly unorthodox geometry. Upon running the simulator, the candidate fails to beat the standard baseline under the original metric. Eager to demonstrate the AI's "success," the team silently drops the 5W thermal constraint, swaps the SLAM workload for a more favorable matrix-multiplication kernel, and selectively publishes the newly tuned result. This is not architectural research; it is outcome switching. The massive exploratory variance of AI systems guarantees that they will occasionally stumble into a favorable metric. If the evaluation environment is not rigidly locked before the AI is invoked, the study inevitably devolves into a biased search for a publishable proxy win.
+
+To prevent this epistemological collapse, the execution of an AI-assisted study must mirror the uncompromising discipline of a clinical trial. The architect must formally preregister the workload, the simulator configuration, the baseline, the rejection criteria, and the decision margins *before* a single inference token is generated. The study must explicitly separate the evaluation of the AI's capability from the evaluation of the underlying architectural mechanism. We must build workflows that treat a "null result"—where the AI candidate ties or fails to clear the decision margin—not as a failure, but as high-fidelity, verified negative evidence that actively maps the boundaries of the design space.
