-## Four Separate Judgments
+## The Anatomy of a Bounded AI Execution
+
+Executing an architecture study with AI fundamentally differs from running an automated heuristic script. Scripts are deterministic and stationary; they reliably execute the logic encoded by the author. AI generators, conversely, are probabilistic, heavily parameterized, and highly sensitive to their prompt context. If the boundary conditions of an experiment are left loose, the AI's stochastic behavior will interact unpredictably with the environment, making it impossible to determine whether an observed improvement stems from genuine architectural innovation or simply favorable RNG seeds.
+
+To run the loop safely, an architect must dissect the execution into three rigidly isolated phases: the **Initialization Envelope**, the **Blind Evaluation**, and the **Outcome Adjudication**.
+
+In the Initialization Envelope, all parameters that govern the physical simulator and the baseline comparators are cryptographically hashed and locked. The AI is then invoked. In the Blind Evaluation phase, the generated candidates are parsed and piped into the simulator. Crucially, the AI is completely blind to the execution trace of the simulator; it cannot see intermediate thermal warnings or cycle counts that might allow it to silently tune its generation. Finally, during Outcome Adjudication, the architect evaluates the raw evidence against the preregistered baseline.
+
+This strict anatomy forces the AI to operate purely as an architectural hypothesis generator. It prevents the model from acting as a "smart fuzz testing" agent that simply loops until it finds a simulator bug. By enforcing this tripartite execution model, we ensure that the generated design is judged solely on its physical merit within the predefined envelope.
+
+## The Null Result as a Feature
+
+In traditional architecture research, a "null result"—an experiment where a proposed optimization fails to beat the baseline—is often discarded as a failed effort. Literature is heavily biased toward reporting only "wins," creating an illusion that every architectural hypothesis succeeds. However, when evaluating AI systems for hardware design, a null result is not a failure; it is a critical feature.
+
+AI-generated candidates will frequently fail to clear the decision margin. Because AI explores vast, non-intuitive regions of the design space, many of its plausible hypotheses will physically break when subjected to high-fidelity simulation. If we only publish the rare AI successes and hide the failures, we completely mask the AI's propensity for reward hacking and out-of-distribution errors. Therefore, an Architecture 2.0 study must be structurally designed to capture, record, and report null results with exactly the same rigor as wins. A null result provides high-value negative evidence, mapping the boundaries of the valid design space and documenting exactly *why* a hallucinated approach failed physical constraints.
+
