+## Clinical Trial Rigor: The Standard of Care
+
+To prevent outcome switching, Architecture 2.0 must treat the baseline design exactly as a medical trial treats the **Standard of Care**. In a clinical trial for a new drug, the "Standard of Care" is the established, proven treatment. The new experimental drug (the AI-proposed architecture) must prove a statistically significant benefit over the Standard of Care (the baseline) without introducing unacceptable side effects (power, area, or thermal violations). Crucially, the protocol defining how the Standard of Care is measured must be locked *before* the first patient is enrolled.
+
+In architecture, the workload, simulator constraints, rejection criteria, and baseline metric must be frozen before the model is ever invoked. Framing the AI as the "experimental intervention" and the baseline as the "standard of care" forces architects to treat simulator configurations as rigid experimental protocols rather than flexible debugging parameters.
