+## Registered Reports: Eliminating Publication Bias
+
+In the scientific community, **Registered Reports** are a publishing format where the hypothesis, methodology, and evaluation criteria are peer-reviewed and accepted *before* the experiment is run. Regardless of whether the final result is a massive success or a complete null result, the paper is published. This structure completely eliminates publication bias, ensuring that rigorous methodology—not just a flashy positive result—is the metric for success.
+
+Architecture 2.0 studies should mirror the philosophy of Registered Reports. The value of an AI-assisted architecture study lies in the rigor of the bounds and the clarity of the evaluation, not in whether the AI managed to beat a human baseline. Running the same comparison under locked rules, and reporting every selected candidate—even when they tie or fail—is the hallmark of a mature engineering discipline.
